  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1366083127" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1366083127" />
    <a title="Tom LA" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4252261-tom-la"><img alt="Tom LA" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578866627p2/4252261.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1366083127?book_show_action=true">Aug 17, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom LA" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom LA" href="/user/show/4252261-tom-la">Tom LA</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1366083127" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3328699223644000390">Given that almost everyone on Goodreads loved this book, I&apos;m genuinely wondering if the author succeeded at &quot;sparking a debate&quot;. I haven&apos;t seen any. Have you?<br/><br/>So here is my lukewarm opinion. It&apos;s not a flat-out negative review, because I found the main points made in this book to be fair and thought-provoking, but Maddow&apos;s arrogant tone and her hate for Reagan ruined the book. <br/><br/>Let me start strong in being controversial here by quoting Justin Logan (Cato Institute) : &quot;The chapters are stapled-toge</span>
  <span id="freeText3328699223644000390" style="display:none">Given that almost everyone on Goodreads loved this book, I'm genuinely wondering if the author succeeded at "sparking a debate". I haven't seen any. Have you?<br /><br />So here is my lukewarm opinion. It's not a flat-out negative review, because I found the main points made in this book to be fair and thought-provoking, but Maddow's arrogant tone and her hate for Reagan ruined the book. <br /><br />Let me start strong in being controversial here by quoting Justin Logan (Cato Institute) : "The chapters are stapled-together polemics about the foibles and screwups in American defense policy. They are decent polemics. They are not, unfortunately, a coherent explanation for why America has drifted away from small-R republicanism and toward empire, much less an explanation for how to turn the tide".<br /><br />Having lived most of my life in Europe, I started reading this book having no idea of who Rachel Maddow was. Then I looked her up and realized she is a left-leaning tv pundit who comes across as intelligent and polished. I watched several of her shows and found them interesting. For TV, that is. <br /><br />I listened to the audiobook, read by the author, and did not enjoy her tone much. I think it depends on where you're coming from: if you like Maddow and her tv show, you will love the book, because it's the same thing, same tone, same style (and nothing more, which is part the problem for me). If you are looking for something to spark a debate, for some provocative thoughts that inspire you to reason, argue, look for facts yourself, you will also probably like this book (but odds are, you are not looking for that). If you are looking for a book that helps you understand a complex topic without bias, and get closer to the Truth, then no - steer away - this is NOT the book for you, because Maddow's recollection of facts, although accurate, is done with a prosecutor's cherry-picking ability. In other words, she NEVER makes a concession, never gives the "on the other hand ... " argument. It's always just one very heavy hand: "This is so obvious! I'm so incredulous! They must be so stupid!". <br /><br />How can you treat incredibly complex issues like these with such superficiality? <br /><br />And by the way, most of this book is a pretty nasty hit piece on Reagan. So, be warned. <br /><br />But aside from the clear bias, the main reason why I did not like the book much is that I found it too “pop” and often off-topic. It reads just like one of Maddows' shows: snarky, fast, easily digested, her points brought home more often by jokes and anectodes rather than deep and serious analysis. <br /><br />Almost as bad as "Jon Stewart politics": perfect to get easy applauses and encouraging laughter from fans, but fundamentally empty - what about trying to get to the objective bottom of a matter? Of course, you can never be too deep on TV, but in a book - especially one that talks about these topics - I was expecting more. There wasn't anthing more. <br /><br />The book is also structured in a very unorganized way. I agree with one reviewer who writes: "The book lacks focus. While it is ostensibly about how the military has lost its way, the chapters switch back and forth on subject without a natural flow. At times throughout, I had to keep asking myself what point she was making [me too. Too many segments are not contextualized]. Her brief review of Operation Urgent Fury (Invasion of Grenada) is an interesting collection of stories and an inside look at Reagan's rationale, but it seemed more a record of a less-than-perfectly-executed military operation than a critique on any particular aspect of military leadership, particularly in the policy arena. Also, it seemed to serve as a way to chip away at Reagan, which she seems to harp on."<br /><br />And how over-long and passionate is her attack on Reagan! Oh my God!! Almost 50% of the book. If you pretend you don't know anything about the man, you will come out of this book convinced that he was absolutely nothing more than a nasty, dishonest moron. <br /><br />As one reviewer puts it: "By "drifting" so far into REAGAN-BASHING she looks sophomoric and detracts from the legitimate points she attempts to make... which are worthy ones about executive power, the constitution, and soldiers' lives". <br /><br />Bias and truth are not mutually exclusive, but by presenting only one side of Ronald Reagan, she does a disservice to history and she deforms the truth, like entering a dark room, pointing the torchlight only to the worst corner of it, and giving a judgement to the whole room.<br /><br />But then again, that's what the mainstream media do every minute of the day. <br /><br />I also said I found it often off-topic because, as another reviewer said well: "Whether she's right or not that the USSR was a benign foreign power whose global ambition was over-hyped by Reagan (while making no mention of Soviet bloc oppression or the invasion of Afghanistan), deficit spending for the 80s military build-up was a flawed policy, and that Reagan was complicit in Iran-Contra -- these items have nothing to do with her central thesis about "Drift." It's interesting stuff at times, but if I was grading her paper I'd tell her to stick to the point." <br /><br />With "Drift", Maddow decided to tackle an immensely complex series of topics (maybe too many) and her conclusions are unfortunately border-line naive and ultimately unconvincing. <br /><br />Naive because, even though I'm very far from being a history expert, and I'm not even American, I got the impression that her thesis is driven by a mythical idea of the United States as it supposedly used to be: she wants to revive the old ideal of America as a "deliberately peaceable nation", not one "always on the lookout for war".<br /><br />It sounds like a grand ideal - and how can you not wish it was true? - but *is it* actually true that the US was a much more peace-seeking nation back then? Or is this the typical "oh, the good old golden days" type of narrative? <br /><br />Let's see: the United States' longest period without a war would appear to be the 33-year period between the end of the Civil War (1865) and the beginning of the Spanish-American War (1898). That's not that long, is it? Is it not naive to think that there is a real difference between a modern President declaring that peace is the highest ideal, and one of the first Presidents making the same declaration? <br /><br />Wasn't America a nation interested in its imperial role, waging countless conflicts again Native Americans, Mexicans, and colonial powers as the new country stretched to encompass a continent? And more importantly, hasn't the world changed beyond recognition and haven't international relations become intertwined in such an unprecedented way that a comparison with a 200 years old foreign policy might be slightly misleading?<br /><br />Maddow analyzes the balance of war-waging power between Executive and Congress. She explains how the US Constitution had intended to set up some safeguards against going to war too easily, namely the requirement of Congress approval, in the absence of which a President could only use military force for a maximum period of 60 days. Maddow argues that this requirement has been stretched and loosened by some Presidents to the point that today the Executive can do pretty much what it pleases when it comes to sending troops to war. I think that is a good point, and seeking a better balance in this highest-level relationship is a worthy cause. <br /><br />As for the use (or non-use) of reserves: when LBJ decided to not call the reserves into the Vietnam war, in Maddow's opinion, he started a dangerous trend of separating the military from the civilian population. That is an ok point, that leads to the wider point that war should be transparent, visible, for everyone to see, for communities to feel the direct pain of, so that Presidents would have much more political capital at risk when committing to the use of force abroad.<br /><br />But I'm really not that convinced about this argument. It sounds too simple. For example: President Eisenhower had seen WWII with his eyes and he was committed to do anything he could to avoid that level of horror and suffering. Therefore, when Foster Dulles proposed to use the CIA to execute covert military actions that would allow the US government to implement its foreign policy goals with an infintely smaller number of casualties (and costs) than in case of a war, Eisenhower found that a preferable option and gave his approval - multiple times. The point is, it is not as simple as Maddow makes it: in some cases, lack of transparency itself was intended by the President as a necessary tool to limit losses, be more efficient and reduce casualties, rather than only as a moronic sense of "I'll do whatever I damn please because I am the President", as she seems to imply. But listening to Prosecutor Maddow, it sounds like every President who mobilized troops was just a child with a big gun. <br /><br />Proposals <br /><br />Towards the end, Maddow offers some proposals aimed at improving the current situation:<br /><br />"1- The saying “Freedom isn’t free” should be more than a bumper sticker, it should be fiscal policy. When we ship troops off to war, we should all pay for it.<br />2- Our Guard and Reserves should be the institutions that weave civilian and military life together. When we ship these men and women off to war, civilian communities all over America should feel that loss".<br /><br />I don't know how realistic this is. Sounds like trying to discourage Presidents from making war, pretty much ... ever. <br /><br />Here is another proposal:<br /><br />"3- Do away with the secret military. If we are going to use drones, the Air Force should operate those drones and pull the trigger. If the CIA is going to do military missions, they need to be accountable like the military is. Same goes for policy makers. Special Forces can be unconstrained and clandestine to the bad guys but not to Congress."<br /><br />I don't know much about this matter, but this book didn't do anything to help me better understand it, or to inform me on how secretive some special ops are - in general - in the eyes of Congress even if they are not supposed to be. Again, only a couple of anectodes. <br /><br />Also: you sure you want to do away with secret drones when your competitors / opponents are China and Russia? Really? <br /><br />And another proposal here:<br /><br />"4- Wind back the privatization of war and the military’s dependence on contractors for what used to be military functions. And when private contractors on our payroll commit illegal acts, they should be prosecuted, not given more contracts."<br /><br />While the author draws deserved attention to the relatively new phenomenon of using civilian contractors to do work previously done by military personnel, she seems to have much more concern with the fact that large companies make money at this enterprise rather than whether it is needed, effective, or what the legal ramifications are. Maddow focuses only on the particular scandal of the private contractors in the Balkans, but fails to make a full, 360 degrees, compelling argument. As always throughout this book, the Devil with the echoing "mwahahahaha" evil laughter is the one and only, Dick Cheney. She wants his head on a plate. <br /><br />And another proposal:<br /><br />"5- Shrink our existing nuclear infrastructure to fit our country’s realistic nuclear mission. Clearly define that mission and only expend what we need to do that."<br /><br />A serious and realistic proposal. Maybe not easy to implement, but very important. <br /><br />Core argument<br /><br />As for Maddow's core argument, that America is sliding down a path of unapproved military conflicts, as I said above, I see her overall point, but I have troubles accepting that this is such a new or recent phenomenon. In fact, if you look at more than 200 military actions in US history, only 11 war declarations have been approved by Congress and 11 times Congress authorized the use of force. <br /><br />Unsurprisingly, Maddow leaves these statistics out. <br /><br />She also leaves out very important facts that a book like this should absolutely have included or at least mentioned:<br /><br />1) Korean War, 1950-1953: Major undeclared war, by executive fiat. First war approved by the UN, a precedent for Clinton with Bosnia. <br /><br />2) Dominican Republic invasion, April 1965 (to 1966). Another adventure by LBJ, simultaneous with his Vietnam escalation. Maddow devotes an entire chapter to the 1983 US invasion of Grenada, with 8,000 American soldiers and 19 of them killed, but nothing about the DR episode, with 42,000 US soldiers, 44 of them killed, and up to 10,000 Dominicans dead. Another executive war.<br /><br />3) Somalia 1992-1993, where a humanitarian mission morphed into US forces taking sides in the civil war, until "Blackhawk Down" hastened US withdrawal.<br /><br />Ok, I just realized I've just written a long essay, when I really meant to just share my personal experience of this book. <br /><br />Here it is in a few words: "Drift" is a bit of a messy argument made by a prosecutor with no interest for objective truth who very often doesn't stick to the point. The main point is a very valuable one, about a balanced approach by the US government to armed conflict and foreign policy. However, do NOT read it if you are looking for an even-handed voice. Maddow sells her opinions (and she does it very well), cherry-picks facts, builds arguments on anectodes and jokes. <br /><br />Entertaining but not deep, thought-provoking but not objective, well-written but not well-organized.<br /><br />And since it's not easy to find reviewers with a similar take to mine, here's a review from the Cato institute: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.cato.org/publications/commentary/book-review-rachel-maddow-abbreviates-history">http://www.cato.org/publications/comm...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="3328699223644000390" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


