  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_455634305" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/455634305" />
    <a title="Jason" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4734912-jason"><img alt="Jason" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1584210891p2/4734912.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/455634305?book_show_action=true">Nov 14, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jason" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jason" href="/user/show/4734912-jason">Jason</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4734912-jason?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4734912-jason?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4734912-jason?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4734912-jason?shelf=war">war</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer455634305" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2608163090774100122">Sure, it&apos;s probably biased. Making a claim and deductively supporting it involves bias. Bias and truth are not mutually exclusive. And Maddow&apos;s claim, that the US executive branch has essentially subverted the Constitution and the ideas of the founding fathers in its evolution toward a secret, unaccountable military disconnected from the government and the public, is awfully damning. Although Drift is occasionally funny, the feeling it leaves with the reader is outrage. <br/><br/>Maddow slays some sacred </span>
  <span id="freeText2608163090774100122" style="display:none">Sure, it's probably biased. Making a claim and deductively supporting it involves bias. Bias and truth are not mutually exclusive. And Maddow's claim, that the US executive branch has essentially subverted the Constitution and the ideas of the founding fathers in its evolution toward a secret, unaccountable military disconnected from the government and the public, is awfully damning. Although Drift is occasionally funny, the feeling it leaves with the reader is outrage. <br /><br />Maddow slays some sacred cows in this book. You could argue that it's an extended hit piece on Reagan, but if Maddow's claims are to be believed he deserved impeachment and criminal prosecution for his unconstitutional forays into Nicaragua and the Middle East, essentially The Iran Contra Affair. On the other hand, she paints other conservatives such as Colin Powell and George H.W. Bush in a mostly favorable light and condemns liberals like Lyndon Johnson, Bill Clinton and even Barack Obama for continuing to exert military oversight that is not only not given to them by the Constitution but expressly, intentionally denied from them by the founding fathers. Unsurprisingly, the villain who lurks in the shadows throughout much of the book is former senator/former secretary of defense/former military contractor CEO/former vice president Dick Cheney. She even dedicates the book to him.<br /><br />In fairness, I searched for decent rebuttals to her claims online. I mostly found ad hominem attacks on Maddow herself: she's a liberal, she's a lesbian, etc. Truthfully, she's also a former Rhodes scholar who holds a doctorate in politics from Oxford--hardly the liberal equivalent of a Beck or Limbaugh. One criticism correctly asserts that she seems to ignore everything that happened between 1776 and 1967, which is true enough but hardly worth discounting her entire claim.<br /><br />Drift is definitely worth reading for some perspective on how we ended up in a country that wages long drawn-out wars which drain the budget while simultaneously complaining about spending money on comparatively less expensive social problems and waging secret CIA sponsored wars with remote controlled drones. You may not like the answers though.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2608163090774100122" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

