  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1912625477" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1912625477" />
    <a title="Emily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2431873-emily"><img alt="Emily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1477433724p2/2431873.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1912625477?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily" href="/user/show/2431873-emily">Emily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/13564710-drift">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2431873-emily?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2431873-emily?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2431873-emily?shelf=american-history">american-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1912625477" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3073409454369501189">The story of <i>Drift</i> goes something like this: once upon a time, the founders of the United States revolted against the British military presence in America and the tax burden of paying for that military. Those same founders were so worried about the problems that come with a standing army that, in the Constitution, they explicitly included several checks and balances to keep the US a peaceable nation, and the military a band of citizen-soldiers. This went along fine until Vietnam, when the presid</span>
  <span id="freeText3073409454369501189" style="display:none">The story of <i>Drift</i> goes something like this: once upon a time, the founders of the United States revolted against the British military presence in America and the tax burden of paying for that military. Those same founders were so worried about the problems that come with a standing army that, in the Constitution, they explicitly included several checks and balances to keep the US a peaceable nation, and the military a band of citizen-soldiers. This went along fine until Vietnam, when the president began to experiment with sending troops to fight in a war that hadn’t been officially declared by Congress. Things began to deteriorate even more rapidly when Reagan, a showman who understood that one key way to keep his popularity level up was to identify an Enemy to fight, increased the defense budget by a staggering 20% per year and started several illegal military operations around the world. He pushed both spending on the military and executive power to extremes never before seen, and presidents since then have followed suit. At this point:<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>By 2011, the total federal R&amp;D budget for alternative energy sources—derided by the right as a huge Obama-era boondoggle—was about $3 billion a year. Meanwhile, the defense R&amp;D budget was $77 billion a year—derided by no one, ever. If you added up what every other country spent on its military in 2001, the US military budget was about half that total; by 2005, those two numbers were equal. In other words, the United States spent as much on national defense as every other country in the world combined. And the Pentagon can now spend those dollars in a way that insulates the decision makers from the political consequences of making life uncomfortable for the voting public.</i>
</blockquote><br />Americans have never been so far away from the consequences of a war. Because the various pieces of the military machine that aren’t the army itself—the CIA, private contractors—are unregulated and unaccountable, and because the president no longer bothers to ask Congress for approval before military maneuvers, the average citizen doesn’t feel the effects of war as they used to, and that inertia drags us further into endless fighting. We’ve drifted away from the ideals enshrined in the Constitution, and it’s had enormous effect on our country.<br /><br />Maddow’s overall point is that it doesn’t have to be this way. We’ve drifted so far away from our ideals not through some vast conspiracy, but through a thousand different decisions in the last fifty years. If we want to reverse this trend, it will take a massive effort, politically and socially, to do so. But it will be worth it, because:<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>Just the nuke budget in the last half of the twentieth century was more than federal spending on Medicare, education, social services, disaster relief, scientific research (of the non-nuclear stripe), environmental protection, food safety inspectors, highway maintenance, cops, prosecutors, judges, and prisons … combined. The only programs that got more taxpayer dollars were Social Security and non-nuclear defense spending.</i>
</blockquote><br />(And FYI, most of those nukes are 40-50 years old, have wing fungus, and are badly in need of repairs—that no US scientist can perform, because the pieces that need updating are too sophisticated and complex. No joke.) <br /><br />The military is a self-sustaining machine at this point. We have the most professional and highly armed military in the world, and the only way to make that profitable is to continue fighting wars. As Maddow says, we’ve created a military superstructure at the expense of all else: we can no longer afford to continue down this road. We’ve focused on the military at the expense of the economy, and it will require a radical shift for us to pull back on executive abuse of power and sending our entire budget into defense. What if we could take all that money and divert it towards education, social services, job training? Isn’t that the world that we want to live in?</span>
  <a data-text-id="3073409454369501189" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


