  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_308210385" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/308210385" />
    <a title="Paul Gleason" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8505940-paul-gleason"><img alt="Paul Gleason" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1417471039p2/8505940.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/308210385?book_show_action=true">Apr 07, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul Gleason" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul Gleason" href="/user/show/8505940-paul-gleason">Paul Gleason</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer308210385" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14021546948406819495">Rachel Maddow is a brilliant, insightful, and passionate public intellectual. There&apos;s a paucity of people like her in the US today, and Drift should be applauded.<br/><br/>Maddow doesn&apos;t really offer anything new here in terms of her political analysis. If you&apos;ve been thinking critically about US history from the beginning of the Cold War to the present day, you won&apos;t find much new information in Drift.<br/><br/>But providing new information isn&apos;t Maddow&apos;s gist. Her impetus is to analyze well-known historical facts</span>
  <span id="freeText14021546948406819495" style="display:none">Rachel Maddow is a brilliant, insightful, and passionate public intellectual. There's a paucity of people like her in the US today, and Drift should be applauded.<br /><br />Maddow doesn't really offer anything new here in terms of her political analysis. If you've been thinking critically about US history from the beginning of the Cold War to the present day, you won't find much new information in Drift.<br /><br />But providing new information isn't Maddow's gist. Her impetus is to analyze well-known historical facts in an attempt to show, in foreign policy at least, the ways in which US history drifts toward the Right, no matter which corporate-sponsored, major-party president currently has his butt in the desk chair of the Oval Office. She carries through her analysis in an engaging, funny, and entertaining way. She's a great teacher.<br /><br />Maddow's thesis is that the US has drifted toward the Right (she never comes out and uses the word "fascist," but she has every right to) because the Congress has begun to cede power to the President in the declaration and, when it comes to the President's corporate backers, the maintenance of war. In addition, she argues that the Abrams Act of the 1960s and the use of the draft made sure that the US people knew that there was a very real price of human lives (read: US deaths) in the waging of war.<br /><br />Now, under Presidents Bush and Obama, war has become a state of life for the US people - something that we expect and don't really notice that much anymore. This is because in assuming dictatorial (fascist?) power in declaring and waging war, the President doesn't engage Congress (the people's body in any good old fashioned democracy) in conversation. He just goes ahead and does whatever he wants. And Congress is more than willing to play along, most likely because its members have the same corporate backers as the President.<br /><br />"Leftist" supporters of President Obama should read this book to learn how, in terms of foreign policy at least, he's on the same page as his predecessor, the man they love to hate. I'm no supporter of either Bush or Obama, and I'm a died-in-the-wool pacifist, so please realize that you're reading the remarks of someone, like Maddow, who is willing to analyze objectively and critically the RECORDS of both men.<br /><br />One final note. Maddow doesn't just complain about the US's drift to the Right. She actually proposes at the end of Drift solutions to the problem. Drift isn't an ironic book or a book that simply bitches about what's wrong with the way US Federal politicians treat the rest of the world and US citizens. Rather, it's an unabashed cry for reason and, dare I say, peace in our time.<br /><br />Rachel Maddow should be applauded for her book and for being so gutsy and courageous. I wish that there were more US citizens like her.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14021546948406819495" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

