    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_316501432" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/316501432" />
    <a title="Tony Heyl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7035744-tony-heyl"><img alt="Tony Heyl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1322103205p2/7035744.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/316501432?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tony Heyl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tony Heyl" href="/user/show/7035744-tony-heyl">Tony Heyl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer316501432" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6930564956154479514">I did something bad. I judged the book by its cover. <br/><br/>Well, really, I judged it by its title. When I first heard about Drift, I thought it was a great idea. Rachel Maddow is one of the very few political talkers that I can listen to because of her calm, well reasoned arguments. The premise of the book, at least as far as I understood it, was to talk about how America became ok with a constant state of war and how war could go on with little opposition. It is an important topic worthy of discussio</span>
  <span id="freeText6930564956154479514" style="display:none">I did something bad. I judged the book by its cover. <br /><br />Well, really, I judged it by its title. When I first heard about Drift, I thought it was a great idea. Rachel Maddow is one of the very few political talkers that I can listen to because of her calm, well reasoned arguments. The premise of the book, at least as far as I understood it, was to talk about how America became ok with a constant state of war and how war could go on with little opposition. It is an important topic worthy of discussion and debate and hopefully action.<br /><br />However, while the writing is fine, the book leaves much to be desired. Maddow focuses almost entirely on how Presidents from LBJ on made the military less accountable to Congress and to the general public. These are important issues, but it ends up being more of a history lesson than an analysis. Yes, Vietnam was conducted poorly by Johnson and Nixon. Yes, Reagan had many problems, most notably Grenada and Iran/Contra. And Yes, the use of contractors under Presidents Clinton, Bush, and Obama make our war efforts far less accountable to the public. These are important things to discuss, but Maddow just leaves it there, putting the onus for this drift towards permanent war solely on the political process.<br /><br />Maddow doesn't talk about the role of the media. She doesn't talk about how movies, television and video games glamorize war. She doesn't talk about the military industrial complex and how politicians protect military spending to advance their own political interests. She doesn't talk about money in politics and the lobbying of defense contractors. She doesn't talk about how the language of war has changed. And she doesn't talk about how the global geo-political picture has altered the public's perception of what war should be and when aggression is needed. <br /><br />This could have been a great book with lots of interesting discussion. Instead it was an ok account of how recent Presidents have altered the role of the Commander in Chief. That wasn't enough for me to be happy with it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6930564956154479514" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

