    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_353695930" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/353695930" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/155663-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581956036p2/155663.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/353695930?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/155663-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/155663-david?shelf=politics">politics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer353695930" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12644720286998091920">The main idea of this book, is that in recent decades it has become too easy for America to go to war. America&apos;s recent presidents have been gradually setting precedents for taking the country to war. Congress has been far too slack in checking this power in the hands of one person. Too often, Congress has not had a healthy debate on the wisdom of going to war. Sometimes presidents have simply acted covertly; Reagan comes to mind with the Iran/Contra affair and the attack on Grenada. At other ti</span>
  <span id="freeText12644720286998091920" style="display:none">The main idea of this book, is that in recent decades it has become too easy for America to go to war. America's recent presidents have been gradually setting precedents for taking the country to war. Congress has been far too slack in checking this power in the hands of one person. Too often, Congress has not had a healthy debate on the wisdom of going to war. Sometimes presidents have simply acted covertly; Reagan comes to mind with the Iran/Contra affair and the attack on Grenada. At other times, Congress simply shirked their duty to debate the issues, and allowed a president to trample over their duty. After all, the U.S. Constitution states that the power to declare war lies <i>with Congress</i>. The framers of the Constitution knew full well that Congress is a slow, deliberative body that has plenty of opinions on any issue. <br /><br />War has been easier for America to wage in recent years, because it has not been a burden on the populace. War is costly, but recent presidents have waged wars while <i>reducing</i> taxes. This puts the burden of the increased national debt on future generations. Also, the increase in private corporations doing many of the jobs that soldiers used to do has removed the necessity of a draft. Technology improvements, like drones, have further removed warfighting from our line of sight.<br /><br />In the last chapter, Maddow lists a set of common-sense recommendations that should reduce the possibility of waging unwise, unpopular wars. Among the recommendations are: 1) Make war painful for the entire country, 2) Remove the secret military, 3) Quit asking the military to make political judgments, 4) allow the National Guard and Reserves to mostly be reserves at home, 5) end the privatization of war.<br /><br />I thoroughly appreciated the arguments that Maddow makes throughout the book. My only complaint is with her writing style; it's full of slang, half-sentences, and glib; she writes exactly like she would speak in an informal conversation, and comes out in a condescending tone. I believe that Maddow could make her excellent points in a better way.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12644720286998091920" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


