<div id="review_375454254" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/375454254" />
    <a title="Socraticgadfly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/110433-socraticgadfly"><img alt="Socraticgadfly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1377632222p2/110433.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/375454254?book_show_action=true">Jul 23, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Socraticgadfly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Socraticgadfly" href="/user/show/110433-socraticgadfly">Socraticgadfly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer375454254" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7939721951064734127">I&apos;m going to be a bit contrarian and down-rate this book. (Ideally, I&apos;d put it at 3.5 stars, maybe 3.75.)<br/><br/>It&apos;s good, good indeed for what it covers. But, it operates under the presumption this is all new.<br/><br/>And, it&apos;s not.<br/><br/>Some US presidents tolerated quasi-official filibustering in Central America back in the 1850s.<br/><br/>Of course, that wasn&apos;t much.<br/><br/>But, since the Spanish-American War, but long before Vietnam, we had plenty of other undeclared wars, without act of Congress.<br/><br/>The 1899-1902 war in the Philippin</span>
  <span id="freeText7939721951064734127" style="display:none">I'm going to be a bit contrarian and down-rate this book. (Ideally, I'd put it at 3.5 stars, maybe 3.75.)<br /><br />It's good, good indeed for what it covers. But, it operates under the presumption this is all new.<br /><br />And, it's not.<br /><br />Some US presidents tolerated quasi-official filibustering in Central America back in the 1850s.<br /><br />Of course, that wasn't much.<br /><br />But, since the Spanish-American War, but long before Vietnam, we had plenty of other undeclared wars, without act of Congress.<br /><br />The 1899-1902 war in the Philippines against people who stupidly believed we wanted them to be free from Spain.<br /><br />Wilson's 1914 invasion of Veracruz, then the Pancho Villa expedition. Then his undeclared intervention in the Russian Civil War.<br /><br />Wilson and almost every president after him through LBJ had undeclared invasions somewhere in the Caribbean.<br /><br /><br />FDR had his undeclared destroyer-vs-submarine war with Germany.<br /><br />Let's not forget the coups in Iran, Guatemala, etc.<br /><br />And, if they were/are "sovereign nations," then every military action against an American Indian tribe without declaration of war fits the bill.<br /><br />Yes, it's worse now than ever, seemingly.<br /><br />But ... is it? There's food for thought the other way.<br /><br />Let's say it is worse now. Maybe it's not that much worse, just we're more aware of it.<br /><br />===<br /><br />If it is worse, though ... Maddow could have spent more time looking at drones, and other modern issues that may only get worse in the future. Or, cyberwarfare, which we're doing right now with things like Stuxnet. Do the drones and viruses make unilateral executive department action even more tempting?<br /><br />===<br /><br />Maddow could further address why Congress doesn't want to be involved in many such cases. And, what was Congress like when McKinley poured tens of thousands of troops into the Philippines? Or during our worst Caribbean adventures?<br /><br />So, the book isn't bad. It could be better on looking at future concerns, though. And, it could be better on looking at the lengthiness of our past history.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7939721951064734127" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


