<div id="review_1960292559" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1960292559" />
    <a title="Lynn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8298997-lynn"><img alt="Lynn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1485389465p2/8298997.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1960292559?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lynn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lynn" href="/user/show/8298997-lynn">Lynn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1960292559" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16053828848904878030">Published 5 years ago but relevant as all hell to today. My favorite quote (among many) from it:<br/><br/>&quot;America&apos;s structural disinclination toward war [by its Constitution requiring the President to obtain the approval of Congress before declaring war] is not a sign that something&apos;s wrong. It&apos;s not a bug in the system. It <i>is</i> the system. It&apos;s the way the founders set us up--to ensure our continuing national health. Every Congress is meddlesome, disinclined toward war, and obstructive of a President&apos;s de</span>
  <span id="freeText16053828848904878030" style="display:none">Published 5 years ago but relevant as all hell to today. My favorite quote (among many) from it:<br /><br />"America's structural disinclination toward war [by its Constitution requiring the President to obtain the approval of Congress before declaring war] is not a sign that something's wrong. It's not a bug in the system. It <i>is</i> the system. It's the way the founders set us up--to ensure our continuing national health. Every Congress is meddlesome, disinclined toward war, and obstructive of a President's desire for it--on purpose...Against a president who [seems] bent on war, Congress [needs] to vigorously (and sometimes preemptively) assert its own authority...[Unfortunately, starting especially with President Reagan, t]he ropes [the founders installed in the Constitution] to lash down presidential war-making capacity, bindings that by design made it hard for an American president to use military force without the nation's full and considered buy-in, have been hacked at with very little appreciation about why they were put there in the first place...It wasn't supposed to be like this."<br /><br />As a Trump supporter told me when I told them I was worried about this man having the means to declare war, "Oh, would you stop worrying so much! He can't declare war without Congress' approval." Uhm, not even considering all the hawks in Congress in the first place, the way the Executive branch's powers have grown since the days of Reagan? How could anybody not be worried?<br /><br />Anyway, an excellent book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16053828848904878030" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


